availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: Section 4 of YBL is a collection of bardic poetry compiled by Seanchán mac Maoil Mhuire Ó Mhaoil Chonaire (Hand63) in 1473. This collection includes 'Fuarus aiscidh gan iarraidh' (cols 182.7-183.18), a praise poem in Classical Gaelic by Tadhg Óg Ó hUiginn (d. 1448) addressed to Alasdair Mac Domhnaill (ob. 1449), Lord of the Isles and Earl of Ross. In the poem, Tadhg Óg rejects Alasdair's invitation to him to come to Scotland and instead exhorts Alasdair to come to Ireland and assert his ancestral right to the kingship thereof. While Tadhg Óg might be Irish, the poem is likely intended for a Scottish audience. It thus sheds light on the Classical Gaelic bardic culture that was common, at least to the elites, of both Scotland and Ireland.

summary.p: 'Fuarus aiscidh gan iarraidh' is the only text in YBL judged at the present time to be of sufficiently certain Scottish relevance to merit transcription. This appears to be the only extant manuscript version of the poem.

note.p: This poem has been edited and translated by McKenna (1939: I, 114–123; II, 69–71), whose edition forms of the basis of that included by McLeod and Bateman (2007: 90–101).

physDesc.p: The part of YBL containing our text (cols 182–83) is laid out in columns, with two columns per page. It is in very good condition, with almost all text clearly legible. All margins are intact around the text. The only problems are caused by smudging and erosion down the centre of col. 182. Our text is the work of a single scribe, Seanchán mac Maoil Mhuire Ó Mhaoil Chonaire (Hand63).

supportDesc.condition: Mostly very good condition, with only occasional smudging

summary.p: As noted above, the section of YBL from which this transcription has been made (section 4) was compiled by Seanchán mac Maoil Mhuire Ó Mhaoil Chonaire (Hand63) in 1473, apparently as an Ó hUiginn poem book. This had been combined with YBL proper, which originated in north Connacht, and other components by the time it was acquired c. 1700 by Edward Lhuyd, probably from one of his contacts in north Connacht. There is no evidence that it ever left that region, let alone Ireland, before its acquisition by Lhuyd.

langUsage.p: As 'Fuarus aiscidh gan iarraidh' was composed by an Irish poet and written out in the extant version by an Irish scribe for use in Ireland (quite possibly all in Connacht), there is no reason to expect any Scotticisms in terms of orthography. They are also unlikely to appear in the language. This is indeed the picture that emerges. The text is in fairly middle-of-the-road Classical Gaelic. There are no prominent archaisms and even features of the earlier language that sometimes endured in the Classical dialect (e.g. a distinctive accusative) are not strongly in evidence. The main distinguishing feature being the slightly archaistic orthography (e.g. “ae(i)” is preferred over "ao(i)"). No Scottish dialectal features are detectable. As it was composed for a Scottish patron, however, it shows that this sort of composition was accessible in an elite context in Gaelic Scotland at the time.
